Or, more commonly with closures:
```rust
let data = vec![1..10];

fn process<T>(iter: Box<dyn Iterator<Item = T> + 'static>) {
    // Wrap the iterator in a closure that captures `data`
    let mut iter_clone: Box<dyn Iterator<Item = T> + 'static> = (
        data.clone(),
        Box::new(iter)
    );
    process_iter(&iter_clone);
}

fn process_iter<T>(iter: &Box<dyn Iterator<Item = T> + 'static>) {
    iter.collect();
}
```

So yes, closures are the standard way to ensure data and iterators stay alive together!
